******
[3]
Date: 20 Jul 2015
Source: Focus Information Agency [edited]
http://www.focus-fen.net/news/2015/07/20/378404/epidemic-plan-put-into-action-in-4-bulgaria-municipalities-over-anthrax-outbreak.html


An epidemic plan will be put into action in 4 Bulgaria municipalities over an anthrax outbreak. Stoyan Pasev, Governor of coastal Varna District, made comments on the matter on Mon [20 Jul 2015], speaking before journalists and announcing some pieces of news, Radio FOCUS -- Varna announced. Pasev stated the epidemic plan would be put into action in 4 municipalities in Varna District over the anthrax outbreak. He added that this was done so that institutions could have readiness as a preventive measure.

The plan would be in force on the territory of 4 municipalities where the meat of the slaughtered animal is thought to have been taken. The municipalities in question are Varna, Provadiya, Vetrino, and Devnya.

Stoyan Pasev said that if it was proven that the 2nd dead animal had died of anthrax, then urgent measures would be taken to provide land to bury the corpse, as transporting it could be dangerous. The vaccination of some 600 animals in the area is expected to start on Mon [20 Jul 2015].

Deputy Minister of Health Vanyo Sharkov, who is also in Varna, when speaking with journalists said that all individuals who had had contact with the infected cow meat, or who had participated in the production of food from it, or who had eaten it had been established. Sharkov attended a sitting of the crisis headquarters in Varna convened over the anthrax case.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Actually, it is perfectly safe to drink milk from cows recently vaccinated with a Sterne-type vaccine. Vaccinated animals should be let out to graze, as housing in summer adds to their stress. Just check them twice a day by hand in case any are showing a temperature. And if an animal should go down with acute anthrax in a cow barn, the chances of other cows exposing themselves to any extravasating contaminated blood is high.

Though not specifically stated, it would be logical to assume that the epidemic implies that the livestock in the Varna, Provadiya, Vetrino, and Devnya municipalities will also be vaccinated.

This northeast region of Bulgaria is regularly afflicted with livestock anthrax outbreaks year after year.
For a map of Bulgaria showing the oblasts and major towns, go to: http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/europe/bulgaria.jpg.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3523608,81. - Mod.MHJ]
